==English==

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|striven|t=to strive}}, from {{der|en|fro|estriver|t=to compete, quarrel}}, from {{der|en|frk|*strīban||t=to exert, make an effort}} from {{der|en|gem-pro|*strībaną}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈstɹaɪv/}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-strive.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|aɪv}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|strives|striving|strove|past2=strived|striven|past_ptc2=strived|past_ptc3=strove|past_ptc3_qual=nonstandard, colloquial}}

# To [[try]] to [[achieve]] a [[result]]; to make [[strenuous]] effort; to try earnestly and persistently.
#: {{ux|en|He '''strove''' to excel.}}
#: {{ux|en|to '''strive''' for the truth}}
# To [[struggle]] in opposition; to be in contention or dispute; to [[contend]]; to [[contest]].
#: {{ux|en|to '''strive''' against fate}}
#* {{RQ:Denham Earl}}
#*: Now private pity '''strove''' with public hate, / Reason with rage, and eloquence with fate.
# To [[vie]]; to [[compete]] as a [[rival]].
#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=IV|passage=[Not] that sweet grove / Of Daphne, by Orontes and the inspired / Castalian spring, might with this paradise / Of Eden '''strive'''.}}

====Usage notes====
* This often occurs as a [[catenative verb]] that takes the ''to infinitive''. See [[Appendix:English catenative verbs]]
* The [[strong]] or [[irregular]] forms "[[strove]]" and "[[striven]]" are more commonly used in print than "[[strived]]".

